{{Quote|When they said no, as ''[Xendor had]'' known they would, he left the Order to found his own academy on Lettow. I accompanied him, and others followed&mdash;first by ones and twos, then in larger groups. These newcomers took to calling themselves the Legions of Lettow, for they swore to defend us and our right to seek knowledge of the Force without the interference of the Jedi hierarchs and their pronouncements about what was correct and what was forbidden.|Filed selections from the debriefing of Arden Lyn|<ref name="EGTW">''[[The Essential Guide to Warfare]]''</ref>}}
'''Lettow''' was a [[Core Worlds/Legends|Core Worlds]] [[Planet/Legends|planet]]. After leaving the [[Jedi Order/Legends|Jedi Order]] in [[24,500 BBY]], the [[Jedi Knight/Legends|Jedi Knight]] [[Xendor]] founded the [[Legionnaire Academy]] on Lettow for studying alternative [[Force-sensitive/Legends|Force-user]] traditions. Other like-minded individuals who came to follow Xendor named themselves the [[Legions of Lettow]], and the group eventually came into [[First Great Schism|conflict]] with the [[Jedi/Legends|Jedi]]. After Xendor's [[Death/Legends|death]] at the [[Battle of Columus]], Jedi [[Army/Legends|armies]] [[Battle of Lettow|attacked]] the Legionnaires at Lettow, who held them off long enough to escape beyond the borders of the [[Galactic Republic/Legends|Galactic Republic]]. Over the subsequent [[Millennium/Legends|millennia]], Lettow became a legendary lost world.

==Description==
Lettow was a terrestrial [[Planet/Legends|planet]]<ref name="GH13" /> located in the [[Lettow system/Legends|Lettow system]], a part of the [[Arrowhead]], or [[The Slice/Legends|the Slice]] portion of the [[Core Worlds/Legends|Core Worlds]]. It was situated near the border of the [[Deep Core/Legends|Deep Core]].<ref name="TEA" />

==History==
{{Quote|Then they came to Lettow to kill the rest of us. I knew there was no hope of victory, only of escape. And so we held Pina's armies off just long enough to seek refuge beyond the Republic's borders.|Filed selections from the debriefing of Arden Lyn|<ref name="EGTW" />}}
In [[24,500 BBY]],<ref name="JvS">[[Jedi vs. Sith: The Essential Guide to the Force (real-life book)|''Jedi vs. Sith: The Essential Guide to the Force'']]</ref> [[Jedi Knight/Legends|Jedi Knight]]<ref name="CSWE Xendor">{{CSWECite|III|341|Xendor}}</ref> [[Xendor]] requested permission from the leadership of the [[Jedi Order/Legends|Jedi Order]] to create an academy devoted to the study of the alternative [[Force-sensitive/Legends|Force-using]] traditions of [[The galaxy/Legends|the galaxy]]. After the request was denied, Xendor left the Order and founded the facility<ref name="EGTW" /> known as the [[Legionnaire Academy]] on Lettow.<ref name="FDCR" /> He was followed by his lover, [[Arden Lyn]], and soon by others who rebelled against the Jedi Order's control over the study of [[The Force/Legends|the Force]]. Those followers of Xendor named themselves the [[Legions of Lettow]], and the disagreements between the Legionnaires and the [[Jedi/Legends|Jedi]] eventually escalated into the conflict known as the [[First Great Schism]].<ref name="EGTW" />

[[File:Arden_Lyn_and_Xendor.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Xendor (right) established the Legionnaire Academy on Lettow.]]
After the Jedi [[Death/Legends|killed]] Xendor at<ref name="EGTW" /> the [[Battle of Columus]],<ref name="BoS">''[[Book of Sith: Secrets from the Dark Side]]''</ref> the Jedi [[Army/Legends|armies]] advanced on Lettow with the intent of killing the rest of the Legions.<ref name="EGTW" /> Lyn, who had inherited the leadership of Xendor's forces,<ref name="TEA" /> realized the only viable strategy was for the Legionnaires to [[Battle of Lettow|hold off]] the Jedi at Lettow, which they did long enough for the former to escape beyond the borders of the [[Galactic Republic/Legends|Galactic Republic]].<ref name="EGTW" /> [[Jedi Master/Legends|Jedi Master]]<ref name="CSWE Pina">{{CSWECite|III|26|Pina, Awdrysta}}</ref> [[Awdrysta Pina]], however, eventually tracked down the fleeing Lyn to the celestial body [[Irkalla]], and during the ensuing [[Duel on Irkalla|confrontation]], Pina placed Lyn in a state of [[Morichro/Legends|stasis]] that lasted until [[4 BBY/Legends|4 BBY]].<ref name="EGTW" />

Lettow fell within the Republic's borders around [[22,000 BBY/Legends|22,000 BBY]],<ref name="TEA" /> but over the subsequent [[Millennium/Legends|millennia]], its location became lost to history, and the events related to it were relegated to the status of legend.<ref name="FDCR" /> In 4 [[Galactic Standard Calendar|BBY]], Lyn was awakened from her stasis by agents of the [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Galactic Empire]] and mentioned Lettow in a debriefing, selections of which were filed by<ref name="EGTW" /> [[Grand Inquisitor/Legends|Grand Inquisitor]] [[Laddinare Torbin]].<ref name="Gamer5">{{GamerCite|5|The Emperor's Pawns}}</ref> By the [[Time/Legends|time]] of the [[Galactic Civil War/Legends|Galactic Civil War]], researchers believed that the [[Ductavis Holocron|holocron]] of the Jedi [[Grand Master/Legends|Grand Master]] and [[Supreme Chancellor/Legends|Supreme Chancellor]] of the Republic [[Biel Ductavis]], who had lived [[Ductavis Era|eleven thousand years]] prior, could allow for the rediscovery of mythical worlds such as Lettow, although the [[Holocron/Legends|artifact]] itself had been lost for millennia on the planet [[Ossus/Legends|Ossus]].<ref name="FDCR" />

==Behind the scenes==
As first documented in the [[1997]] book ''[[Star Wars: The Annotated Screenplays]]'' by [[Laurent Bouzereau]], the name "Lettow" originated in [[George Lucas]]'s [[1974]] [[The Star Wars first draft|first script draft]] for the [[1977]] [[original trilogy]] film, [[Star Wars: Episode IV A New Hope|''Star Wars'': Episode IV ''A New Hope'']]. In the draft, "Legions of Lettow" was a name used for a faction that would ultimately morph into the [[Sith/Legends|Sith]] that served as the antagonists of the trilogy.<ref name="Annotated">''[[Star Wars: The Annotated Screenplays]]''</ref>

The name of the Legions of Lettow was reclaimed for [[canon]]ical use with respect to the [[Star Wars Legends|''Star Wars'' Legends]] continuity in the [[2002]] ''[[Power of the Jedi Sourcebook]]'', which was published for use with [[Wizards of the Coast]]'s ''[[Star Wars Roleplaying Game]]''.<ref name="PotJS">''[[Power of the Jedi Sourcebook]]''</ref> [[Daniel Wallace]] and Fry's [[2009]] reference book ''[[The Essential Atlas]]'' subsequently established that Lettow was a distinct celestial body and placed it in grid square M-11.<ref name="TEA" />

